=== TASK ===
# Reporting & Performance

## Overview
Develop a production-ready Reporting & Performance module for LuxeFlow CRM that delivers an analytics workspace for bookings, revenue, commissions KPIs, conversion, pipeline, and agent performance. The page supports filters by resort, agent, and date range, and provides exportable visualizations. It is tightly integrated with the existing system’s reporting, exports, and scheduled reports capabilities, and includes a pre-built set of dashboards for bookings, revenue, commissions, and team performance. The implementation must be robust, scalable, and safe for null/undefined data, with strict runtime safety rules applied across frontend and backend layers.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- The Reporting & Performance page is an analytics workspace presenting key performance indicators (KPIs) and operational metrics centered on bookings, revenue, commissions, conversion, and sales pipeline. It enables filtering by resort, agent, and date range, and supports export of visualizations and data as CSV/PDF, plus schedule-based report exports.

Goals:
- Provide an at-a-glance view of performance through KPI cards (bookings count, total booking value, total commission, conversion rate).
- Enable deep dives via interactive breakdowns (by agent, by resort, by source) and a conversion/pipeline funnel (quote → confirmed).
- Support export workflows (CSV/PDF) and scheduling of recurring reports.
- Include a Custom Report Builder to tailor ad-hoc analytics.
- Ensure seamless integration with existing platform security, data models, and permissions (Admin, Agent, Ops, Finance).

Features connected:
- Reporting, Exports & Scheduled Reports: Financial and operational reporting with schedule exports, CSV/PDF export, and pre-built dashboards for bookings, revenue, commissions, and team performance.
- Sample Data Seed: Utilized for demos and testing; ensure the page gracefully handles empty seeds or partial data.

UI elements and guidance:
- KPI Cards: Four to six cards showing bookings count, total booking value, total commission, conversion rate, pipeline stage counts, and average deal size.
- Date Range Selector: Presets (Last 7 days, 14 days, 30 days, YTD) plus custom range with validation.
- Breakdown Visualizations: 
  - Agent breakdown: indicator of performance per agent with sortable columns or mini-charts.
  - Resort breakdown: performance by resort with filters and ranking.
  - Source breakdown: channel/source effectiveness.
- Pipeline Funnel: Visual representation of stages from Quote to Confirmed with conversion rates between stages.
- Exports: Buttons and dropdowns to export current view to CSV or PDF; schedule exports with recurrence rules.
- Custom Report Builder: UI to assemble metrics, filters, and groupings into a saved report.
- Data Guidance: Tooltips and contextual help for metrics definitions and date normalizations.
- Visual guidance: Clean, minimal charts with ample whitespace and olive-green accent highlights; no heavy grid backdrops; data-first emphasis.

Visual style:
- Align with the project’s LuxeFlow design system, including typography, color palette, and component behavior described below.

Connected APIs/Integrations:
- No external APIs required for MVP; all data sources are within the existing Supabase/Postgres setup or internal APIs. The page should be designed to be API-agnostic to allow future integrations.

---

## Components to Build
- ReportingDashboard (page container)
- KPICard (reusable metric tile)
- DateRangePicker (with presets and validation)
- BreakdownPanel (agent, resort, source—toggleable)
- PipelineFunnel (staged visualization)
- DataTable or GridView (for sortable lists, with guard rails for null)
- ChartPlaceholder (for future charts; to be replaced with actual charts; ensure accessibility and aria labels)
- ExportPanel (CSV/PDF export actions and schedule exporter)
- CustomReportBuilder (UI to configure and save ad-hoc reports)
- SeedDataVerifier (utility to confirm seed data presence and handle empty seeds gracefully)

Technical details:
- All data-driven renderings must defensively guard against null/undefined values.
- Use data ?? [] for lists from API responses.
- Validate array shapes with Array.isArray checks before mapping or reducing.
- Use useState<T[]>([]) defaults for array-based state.
- Destructure API responses with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}.
- Ensure optional chaining when digging into nested API/DB results: data?.metrics?.bookingCount etc.

---

